<font color="#FF0000">GOING ALL THE WAY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  9 23:33:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Angela proposes one answer, whether &quot;she&quot; intends it or not.  There are many, including a number of vets, who believe we should have gone all out to &quot;win&quot; the war.  After all, it was a war.  In fact, nuclear weapons were considered at least once, but were rejected for 2 very good reasons:<br>
1) militarily, they just didn't make sense.  What the hell would we have hit with the damn things?<br>
2) politically, there is no way the US could have withstood the international firestorm that would have followed their use.  My dad worked on the Manhattan Project in WWII.  Today, lots of folks are second-guessing our use of nuclear weapons to end WWII; imagine what would happen if the issue was less clear (as it would have been in 'Nam).<br>
I think similar arguments apply to less extreme attempts to go &quot;all out&quot; (invading North Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos and staying there, sending many more combat troops, etc.).  There is an added wrinkle - does anyone think the NVA would have given up?  Ain't no way - those dudes were going to hang in there NO MATTER WHAT WE DID.  Better to get out most skosh, and let them folks figure it out.  Better yet, don't go there in the first place.  We made a lot of promises to the SVN that we just couldn't keep, and those folks are still paying for it.<br>
As for praying to Jesus, or whoever, - sorry, I just don't see it.  I know I'm steppin on some religious toes here, but that suggestion just doesn't cut it.  I didn't see any miracles in 'Nam - all I saw was a world of shit.
